Title: The Last of England
Description: A man and a woman sit side by side in a roundel holding each other's hands. They are sitting on a boat called Eldorado. She holds a baby in her left arm, its hand can be seen through a gap in her shawl. They are protected from the wind and spray by an umbrella held by the man. Behind them is a variety of figures including a little girl eating an apple and a man in a top hat shaking his fist. There is also a boy climbing into a lifeboat. In the background to the right is the sea, white cliffs and another boat.
Subject: Oil Paintings (Visual Works), Paintings (Visual Works), Pre-Raphaelite

Title: Beata Beatrix
Description: A young woman is shown seated and half length at the moment of suspension between life and death. A bird drops it's red poppy between her open hands. In the background Dante is shown looking across to the figure of Love. The frame has four incised roundels, one on each side.

Title: The Annunciation
Description: The Virgin Mary stands on the right in an interior setting.  She wears a purple dress with wide blue sash and veil with a red head band.  She is turned to the left and holds the red wool she has been spinning in her right hand.  The unspun wool rests on the bench she has been sitting on.  The angel Gabriel floats on the left just before the doorway.  His wings cross over and cover his legs.  Two small angelic heads and a dove hover at the apex of the image.
Subject: Oil Paintings (Visual Works), Paintings (Visual Works), Pre-Raphaelite

Title: The Nativity
Description: Young Mary kneels in the centre of the composition winding a white cloth around a infant Christ who is held by an angel on the right.  Mary wears a white robe and her long red hair falls loosely over her shoulders.  An angel on the left holds a lamp to aid Mary.  In the background there is a manger, with floor strewn with straw.  The wings of the angels frame the bottom of the composition.  At the top of the image is a hole in the ceiling through which can be seen the heads of three angels.
Subject: Oil Paintings (Visual Works), Paintings (Visual Works), Pre-Raphaelite
WorkMedium: Oil and gold leaf on canvas

Title: The Woman of Samaria
Description: Christ Sits By A Well In The Centre Of A Landscape Scene. He Is Dressed In Long Red Robes. He Sits On A Dark Blue Cloth Draped Over The Wall Of The Well, With His Right Arm Leaning Against A Rock. The Well Is On The Right And A Rope For The Bucket Is Tied To A Rock In The Foreground. On The Left, Behind Christ, Is A Flight Of Steps. A Woman Dressed In Long Blue Robes And Carrying A Water Urn On Her Head Descends The Steps. In The Background There Are Two Stone Walls And In The Distance Is A Town. The Figures Are Surrounded By Lush Vegetation And Just Behind Christ, On The Right, Is The Trunk Of A Large Tree.

The Second Man Wears A Boater-Style Hat And Is Pointing To Something With His Right Hand.
Subject: Drawings (Visual Works), Pre-Raphaelite

Description: Costume Study - A Dominican Monk of 1200AD from Bonnard's 'Costume Historique' - A Full-Length, Standing Monk With Short Hair Wearing Long Robes And A Hooded Cloak. The Hood Is Not Up. He Is Pointing With His Right Hand And In His Left Hand He Holds An Open Book And A Crucifix.
Subject: Drawings (Visual Works), Pre-Raphaelite

Description: Costume Study - an Illustration of fifteenth-century Torture of 1400 AD from Bonnard's 'Costume Historique' - On The Left Is A Male Figure Kneeling On One Leg Which Is Held Stocks. He Leans On The Chair Behind Him With His Right Hand. His Left Hand Is Raised In Front Of His Face. He Wears A Simple Crown, A Short Tunic And Close Fitting Trousers With Long Pointed Feet. He Looks Scared. On The Right Is A Standing Male Figure (the Page Has Been Cut And The Top Part Of His Head Cropped). He Wears A Short Tunic, Close Fitting Trousers But Separate Shoes With Long Points. He Also Wears A Hood With A Long Tail Known As Liripipe. He Is Standing In Front Of The Kneeling Man And Gesturing With Both Hands. He Has An Angry Expression.
Subject: Drawings (Visual Works), Pre-Raphaelite

Description: Costume Study - An Illustration with four Figures of 1200AD from Bonnard's 'Costume Historique' - On The Left Is A Full-Length Standing Figure In Profile To The Left (the Page Has Been Cut And Their Body Has Been Cropped). They Are Wearing A Floor-length Robe And Hood. On The Right Of This Figure Is A Full-Length Standing Young Woman. She Wears A Simple Crown And A Long Robe, With Wide Sleeves, Decorated With A Pattern Of Foliage. She Holds Out Her Right Hand To A Man On The Far Right Who Appears To Be Placing A Ring On Her Extended Index Finger Although No Ring Is Drawn In. In The Centre Is A Full-Length Standing Male Figure In A Long Robe And Hood. On The Right Is Full-Length Standing Man Turned Towards The Young Woman. He Wears A Long Robe With Wide Sleeves And A Hat. He Holds The Edge Of His Robe In His Left Hand And Extends His Right Hand Towards The Woman.
Subject: Drawings (Visual Works), Pre-Raphaelite

Description: Costume Study - An Illustration with three Figures of 1400 AD from Bonnard's 'Costume Historique' - In The Centre Of The Interior Scene Sits A Man With One Hand On His Hip. He Wears A Long Robe And A Tall, Bucket Shaped Hat. Behind Him Hangs A Patterned Piece Of Fabric. He Is Looking At The Man On The Left Who Stands Before A Lectern Holding A Open Book. He Wears A Long Robe. One The Right Stands A Man Wearing A Short Tunic, Pulled In At The Waist With Long Sleeves, And Close Fitting Trousers With Long Pointed Toes.
Subject: Drawings (Visual Works), Pre-Raphaelite

Title: Psyche Rescued by Naiads
Description: Oval. Mythological Scene. Psyche Sits At The Centre Of The Composition: Her Left Arm Outstretched, Her Right Hand Clutching A Piece Of Fabric, Her Eyes Gazing Upward.She Is Supported By Four Female Naiads: Two Support Her Upper Body From Behind, Two Support Her Lower Body On The Left. A Male Naiad Can Be Seen Behind The Group, On The Far Right. The Scene Is Set In A River, As Indicated By The Gushing Water At The Bottom Of The Composition. A Tree Trunk Frames The Left Of The Composition, And Mountains Can Be Seen In The Distance.

Title: King Lear
Description: Sketch of Lear questioning Cordelia / Alfred the Great - Compositional Sketches - Recto: In A Room With Tall Arched Windows, King Lear Sits On A Raised Throne Holding A Sceptre In His Right Hand And An Orb In His Left, Leaning Towards Cordelia Who Stands On The Right. Between Them Is A Map And A Male Figure. Behind Cordelia Is Another Figure, Only Slightly Drawn.  To The Left Are Goneril, Regan And Cordelia In Pencil, Regan With Her Hand Outstretched And Cordelia Only Faintly Drawn. Above This Are Three Figures, In Pencil. In The Centre Is A Female Figure Restrained By The Two Figures Either Side Of Her, Both Faintly Drawn. Verso: Seated King Alfred Surrounded By Figures.  In His Right Hand He Holds A Stick And Is Drawing With It On The Ground. His Left Hand Is Stretched Out To The Side.  On The Right In Front Of Him Is A Male Figure Is Bending Over And Pointing To The Diagram That Has Been Drawn. This Figure Is Sketched By Itself In The Top Right-hand Corner. To The Left Of This Figure Are A Figure Reclining And Two Figures Sitting Together.
Subject: Drawings (Visual Works), Pre-Raphaelite
WorkMedium: Iron Gall Pen And Ink Over Pencil On Paper

Title: The Death of Sir Galahad while taking a Portion of the Holy Grail administered by Joseph of Arimathea
Description: The Death of Sir Galahad while taking a Portion of the Holy Grail administered by Joseph of Arimathea - Two Full-Length Male Figures Are Identified By Archaic Writing As Joseph Of Arimathea And Sir Galahad. A Youthful Sir Galahad, In Profile To The Left, Dressed As A Knight With A Crown On His Head And A Sword At His Side, Kneels To Receive The Eucharistic Wafer And A Ceremonial Kiss On The Forehead From Joseph Of Arimathea Who Is Standing In Profile To The Right, Wearing A Priestly Robe. Around The Haloed Main Figures Are Three Roundels, Their Subjects Identified By Writing Of The Same Style: The Roundel On The Left Depicts Sir Galahad And The Two On The Right Embracing Couples; Tristan And Iseult In The Top Right And Sir Launcelot And Queen Guinevere Immediately Below.
Subject: Drawings (Visual Works), Pre-Raphaelite
WorkMedium: Pen And Ink Over Pencil On Paper

Title: Morgan-le-Fay
Description: The Sorceress Morgan-le-fay Turned To The Left And Wearing A Green Robe With Various Additional Layers Including A Yellow Apron Decorated With Pict Symbols And A Leopard Skin. Her Head Is Tilted Slightly Backwards. She Is Looking Down At An Open Book On The Ground And Has Her Mouth Open As If Speaking. Her Arms Are Stretched Out In Front Of Ther And She Holds A Lit Dragon-shaped Lamp In Her Right Hand. In Front Of Her Is Black Robe With Red Details Draped Over The Top Of A Dresser. Small Tongues Of Flame Sprout From The Draped Robe. Between Morgan And The Robe Is A Lit Tripod Brazier And Behind This Is A Frienze Decorated With Egyptian Animal Gods And Japanese Roundels. On The Right Behind Morgan Le Fay Is A Loom With Two Owls Nestling On Top Of It.
Subject: Oil Paintings (Visual Works), Paintings (Visual Works), Pre-Raphaelite

Title: Medea
Description: Half-length Seated Figure Of Medea. Her Head Is Tilted Slightly To Her Right And She Faces The Spectator. She Claws At Her Red Necklace Whilst Pouring Liquid From A Beaker Into A Lit Burner. Her Long Hair Is Loose. She Wears A Headband, Long Earrings And A White Dress. On The Left In The Foreground Is A Pair Of Copulating Toads And A Small Egyptian Sculpture. On The Right Is A Abalone Shell. She Sits In Front Of A Gold Background Decorated With A Ship On The Left, Flying Cranes And The Golden Fleece Hanging In A Grove Of Trees. Below The Gilt Decoration Is A Dragon, His Legs On The Left And His Head On The Right.
Subject: Oil Paintings (Visual Works), Paintings (Visual Works), Pre-Raphaelite
WorkMedium: Oil On Panel With Gilded Background

Behind Her On The Left Is Another Woman, Her Body Turned To The Left And Looking Back Towards The Viewer. At The Back Of The Kitchen Is A Set Of Shelves, Displaying Metalware. In The Foreground, On The Right, A Leopold Is Lying Down, Behind Which An Incense Burner Is Smoking, And On The Left A Jug Has Toppled Over Spilling Liquid Onto The Ground. Title: The Feast of Herod
Description: Copy After A Painting By Peter Paul Rubens, A Version Of Which Is In The National Gallery Of Scotland, Edinburgh. Feast Scene Set In A Classical Interior. A Long White Table Occupies The Centre Of The Composition, Surrounded By Figures (seated Guests, Servants And Guards). Herod And Herodias Are Seated On A Dias At The Far Right, Covered By A Baldachin. Salome, Who Wears A Red Dress And Is Stood In Front Of The Table, Presents A Platter With The Head Of John The Baptist To Herod. Herod Surveys The Head With Disgust, Herodias Looks At Him Whilst Pointing To The Head With A Fork In Her Right Hand.

Title: The Singing of Love
Description: Four Male Figures And Three Female Figures Sit Along A Bench: All Seven Are Full-Length Nudes Apart From One Woman Wearing A Flowing Robe. Their Feet Rest On A Plinth On Which Their Titles Are Inscribed: Somnus, Memoria, Morpheus, Amor, Voluptas, Libido And Mors. In The Centre The Winged And Haloed Figure Of Love (Amor) Holds A Branch And, Mouth Open, Appears To Be Singing. The Figures Wear Or Hold Symbols Which Are Related To Their Titles. Further Attributes Appear Behind The Figures And At Their Feet.

Title: A Nightmare
Description: A Landscape Scene With A Braying Ass Ridden By John Everett Millais Dressed In Armour. A Small Figure Of Dante Gabriel Rossetti Sits On His Knee, And A Smaller Figure Of William Holman Hunt Clings To His Back. Millais Carries Peacock Feathers, A Tin Of Paint And A Daubing Pole. Hunt Has A Bundle Of Paint Brushes Strapped To His Back. The Ass Has The Words 'J R Oxon' Stamped On Its Hind Quarters. In The Background Is A River. On The Right Bank Are The Three Figures Of Raphael, Titian And Michelangelo, A Palette And Brushes And A Scroll Inscribed 'orate P[ro] Nobis' (Pray For Us). Behind Them Are Trees And A Bridge. On The Left Is A Tower. Below The Image Is A Scroll Of Mock Medieval Satirical Verses In Gothic Style Text. Below This Is The Name And Details Of The Publisher And The Date Of Publication.

Title: The Ford
Description: The Painting Depicts A River Bank, With A River To The Right And Ruined Buildings To The Left, In The Distance Is Another Building And A Wooden Bridge Across The River. At The Centre Are Two Men On Horses (one White, One Brown). The Man On The White Horse Talks To A Figure, Dressed In Red, Seated By The Bank On The Right, Further Along The Bank Are Three Figures Bathing. The Man On The Brown Horse Looks To A Group Of Three Figures On The Left, Sat And Stood In Front Of A Building. In Front Of The Group Is A Dog. Behind The Group, Is A Figure Walking Down Steps From A Building.

Title: A River Scene
Description: Marine Painting. River Scene, With River Bank To The Right. On The River Are Numerous Small Fishing Vessels With White Sails, Which Can Be Seen Into The Distance. In The Left Lower Foreground Is A Fishing Boat, Without Sails, With Figures Inside. To The Right, Further Back, Are Two Other Fishing Boats Without Sails, With Figures Inside. On The Bank, Towards The Centre, Is A Dilapidated Cottage. To The Right Of The Cottage, A Horse-drawn Cart And Another Figure Riding A Horse Make Their Way Along The Bank. The Upper Two-thirds Of The Painting Are Sky. The Painting Is Very Tonal, Produced In Muted Colours.

Title: Susanna And The Elders
Description: History Painting. At The Centre Of The Painting Is Susanna, Her Right Hand Opened And In Front Of Her, Her Left Hand Clutching Drapery To Her Breast. Her Body Faces To The Left, But Her Head Is Turned Towards Two Men On The Right (the Elders). The Man On The Far Right, Holds Out His Left Hand To Touch Susanna's Arm, Whilst Holding His Right Hand To His Mouth. The Man To His Left, Wearing A Turban, Holds Susanna's Drapery With His Right Hand, Attempting To Remove It From Her Shoulder. The Scene Is Set In A Garden With Classical Architecture (the Baths). To The Upper Left Is A Sculpture Of A Putto Riding A Sea Creature (?).
Subject: Oil Paintings (Visual Works), Paintings (Visual Works)

Title: Landscape near Rome with a View of the Ponte Molle
Description: Landscape. The Painting Depicts The Ponte Molle On The Right, As Seen From The Left Bank Of The River Tiber. On The River Is A Small Fishing Boat. The Bridge Is Framed By A Tree At The Centre-left. In The Left Background Is A Group Of Buildings, In Front Of Which Is A Wooden Bridge, Crossed By A Figure And Surrounded By Livestock. In The Right Foreground Are Two Figures: A Girl Playing With A Dog And A Seated Man With A Staff. The Scene Is Takes Place At Sunset.
Subject: Oil Paintings (Visual Works), Paintings (Visual Works), Landscapes (Representations)

Title: The Music Lesson
Description: Genre Scene. The Painting Shows A Young Woman Wearing A White Satin Dress, Seated In The Centre And Turned To The Right, Playing A Muselar. Standing Behind The Young Woman To The Right, Is Her Music Teacher, Who Looks Down At His Student. To The Left Is A Serving Woman, Holding A Jug And Gazing To The Right. On The Floor, Near The Bottom Left Corner, Is A Small Dog. The Scene Is Set In A Darkened Room, There Is A Mirror Hung On The Wall To The Right And A Table Covered By An Islamic Carpet In The Bottom Right Corner.
Subject: Oil Paintings (Visual Works), Paintings (Visual Works)

Title: Orpheus Returning from the Underworld
Description: Mythology Set Within A Landscape. On The Left Is A Vaulted Cistern, Framed By A Larger Arch In The Foreground, Both Are Crumbling And Covered In Plant Life. In The Background, To The Right, Are A Bridge And Building Set In A Green Landscape. In The Distance Is An Erupting Volcano. In The Lower Right Foreground Is An Arched Entrance Way Set Within A Mound. In Front Of This, The Story Of Orpheus And Eurydice Takes Place: As Orpheus Turns To Look At Back At Eurydice, She Is Dragged Into The Underworld. At The Centre, Is A Group Of Naked Figures. At The Upper Right Is A Man Hanging From A Joist, A Demon Reading A Text Sits On Top Of The Rope.
Subject: Oil Paintings (Visual Works), Paintings (Visual Works), Landscapes (Representations)

Title: An Allegory of Misrule
Description: Allegorical Scene. At The Centre, Venus Surrounded By A Retinue Of Satyrs And Putti, Advances Toward The Sea Shore At The Lower Right Of The Painting. Emerging From The Sea, Lower Right, Are A Group Of Sea Creatures, Tritons And Nerids. In The Left Foreground, Father Time Gestures To A Melancholy And Stupefied Group Representing Science And The Arts. In The Background, A Raging Battle Takes Place Between Lapiths And Centaurs. The Scene Is Set In A Landscape, Framed By A Silvery Tree At The Centre And Ruined Classical Architecture On The Left.
Subject: Oil Paintings (Visual Works), Paintings (Visual Works)

Title: Portrait of a Woman
Description: The Sitter Is Shown Mid-length Against A Dark Background, With Her Body Turned To The Left And Her Head Facing Forward Looking Towards The Viewer. Her Left Arm Rests By Her Side, She Holds A Closed Fan In Her Right Hand. She Wears A Black Gown (a 'tabbaard') With Floral Motifs, With The Forepart (the 'schoot') Lined In A Contrasting Red. The Sleeves Under The Gown Are Embroidered With A Gold Floral Motif. The Sitter Wears A Large Ruff, And Elaborate Lace Headpiece And Sleeves. She Wears Gold Bracelets, Ring, Necklace, And Chain.

Title: Portrait of Richard (Dicky) Bateman
Description: Portrait. The Figure Is Shown Mid-length, Positioned Behind An Arched Window. The Window Ledge Is Draped In A Red Fabric, There Is A Grisaille Frieze Below The Ledge. The Figure Stands In Front Of A Curtain, Pulled To The Left To Reveal A Building In The Right Background; ' La Chinois' Painted Red, Blue And Yellow And Decorated With Carved Dragons. The Figure Himself Is Shown Wearing A Richly Embroidered Chinese Gown, His Hand Points To A Chinese Calligraphic Scroll Resting On A Ledge In Front Of Him.

Title: The Betrayal Of Christ
Description: History Painting. Christ Stands Centre-right, His Left Hand Held Out To The Side, His Right Hand On His Chest. In The Lower Left Are Three Figures, Disciples And Officers, On The Ground, Reacting To The Arrest. In The Background, Behind Christ, A Disciple Moves To Cut Off The Ear Of An Officer With A Sword. The Scene Is Set In The Garden Of Gethsemane, As Indicated By The Plant-life Lower-right. The Air Is Filled With Smoke, Created By The The Lantern On The Right.

Title: The Wild Swans (The Twelve Brothers Turned Into Swans)
Description: Its 'sister' painting 'The Twelve Brothers' Purchased In 2002 (2002P35) Was Painted In 1898 And Represents An Earlier Stage In The Re-telling Of The Grimm Brothers Fairy Tale, Where The Red-haired Woman Is Being Courted By The Prince And His Entourage (personifications Of Georgie Cave France And Arthur Gaskin Himself). The Story Tells Of A King And Queen Who Have 12 Sons. The King Is Determined That The Crown Must Pass To A Daughter And If The Queen Gives Birth To A Girl He Will Have His Sons Executed. To Protect Them, The Queen Sends Them To Live Deep In The Forest Where They Find An Old Enchanted Cottage. A Daughter Is Born And Is Raised As A Solitary Child In The Court. One Day She Finds 12 Shirts In The Palace Laundry And Asks Her Mother Who They Belong To. The Queen Confesses And Tells Her About Her Brothers And The Threat To Their Lives. The Princess, Now Aged 10, Sets Off To Find Them In The Forest. She Eventually Discovers Their Cottage And Goes In. Although The Brothers Had Sworn To Kill Her If They Ever Met Her, They Are So Touched By Her Kindness That They Relent And Ask Her To Join Them In Hiding. They All Live Happliy Together Until One Day The Princess Unwittingly Picks Twelve Magic Lilies Growing In The Cottage Garden. Her 12 Brothers Are Immediately Turned Into Swans And Fly Away. A Witch Appears And Tells Her That They Cannot Be Changed Back To Human Form Unless She (the Princess) Remains Silent For 7 Years And Knits 12 Magic Shirts For Them Made Of Nettles. She Vows To Do So And Lives Up A Tree In A Distant Forest To Avoid Any Temptation To Speak. However, A Young King Out Hunting With His Courtiers Sees Her In The Tree And Is Captivated By Her Beauty. They Marry Though She Remains Dumb And He Does Not Know She Is Of Noble Birth. Her Mother In Law, Who Thinks Her Son Has Married Beneath Him Conspires To Accuse Her Of All Kinds Of Crimes. Unable To Speak Up In Her Own Defence She Is Soon Condemned To Burn At The Stake. It Is 7 Years To The Day When She Is Led To The Stake And Just As The Fire Is Lit She Sees Twelve Swans Flying In Formation Above. They Swoop Down And Scatter The Burning Twigs And Free Her From Her Bonds. She Places A Nettle Shirt Over Each Of Them And She Is Joyfully Reunited With Her 12 Brothers. At Last She Can Speak And Tells Her Husband Who She Is And Of The Wrongs Done To Her. The Evil Mother In Law Is Boiled In Oil And Everyone Lives Happily Ever After. The 1928 Painting Illustrates The Moment The Princess Is Rescued And Begins To Distribute The Shirts.
Subject: Tempera Paintings, Paintings (Visual Works)
WorkMedium: Tempera On Wood Panel; Very Light Varnish
